Here's a recommended structure:

**1. Make HTTP calls injectable**

```csharp
// In your MCP server project
public class MyTool
{
    private readonly HttpClient _httpClient;

    public MyTool(HttpClient httpClient)
    {
        _httpClient = httpClient;
    }

    public async Task<string> GetDataAsync(string id)
    {
        var response = await _httpClient.GetAsync($"/api/data/{id}");
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync();
    }
}
```

**2. Create a test project**

```bash
dotnet new xunit -n MyMcpServer.Tests
cd MyMcpServer.Tests
dotnet add reference ../MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj
dotnet add package Moq           # or NSubstitute
dotnet add package RichardSzalay.MockHttp  # mock HttpClient easily
```

**3. Test with a mocked `HttpMessageHandler`**

```csharp
using RichardSzalay.MockHttp;

public class MyToolTests
{
    [Fact]
    public async Task GetDataAsync_ReturnsExpectedResult()
    {
        // Arrange — fake the HTTP layer
        var mockHttp = new MockHttpMessageHandler();
        mockHttp.When("/api/data/123")
                .Respond("application/json", """{"name":"test"}""");

        var httpClient = mockHttp.ToHttpClient();
        httpClient.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com");

        var tool = new MyTool(httpClient);

        // Act
        var result = await tool.GetDataAsync("123");

        // Assert
        Assert.Contains("test", result);
    }
}
```

**Key principles:**

| Concern | Approach |
|---|---|
| **Inject `HttpClient`** | Use constructor injection so tests can supply a fake |
| **Mock at `HttpMessageHandler`** | `MockHttpMessageHandler` lets you define canned responses per URL/method |
| **No wrapper interfaces needed** | `HttpClient` is already designed for this via its handler pipeline |
| **Test tool logic, not HTTP** | Verify your parsing, error handling, and return values |

**Project layout:**

```
src/
  MyMcpServer/
    Tools/MyTool.cs
tests/
  MyMcpServer.Tests/
    Tools/MyToolTests.cs
```

This keeps your tests fast, deterministic, and independent of any external service.
